London House is a kitchen record dating from the years 1612 to 1614. These sources are perhaps most similar to an account book, in that it tracks expenses for the house on a weekly basis. 
However, unlike most account books, a kitchen record focuses solely on the food being purchased for the house every week. What makes this record particularly interesting is it not only tracks 
the food purchased, but what was consumed, the price, and what was left over for the coming weeks. This information was laid out in varying formats but had four consistent categories: “Venit,” 
the type of food purchased, “Expence,” how much of the food was consumed, “Valet,” the price to purchase the food item, and “Remanet,” the amount, if any, let over for the coming weeks. 
